newsitem.title: USA: US W.Coast prods mixed on weak NYMEX, low supplies.
newsitem.headline: US W.Coast prods mixed on weak NYMEX, low supplies.

text.p: U.S. West Coast spot products prices were mixed late Tuesday amid a NYMEX collapse and perceived shortages caused by local refinery outages.
Front-month NYMEX gasoline fell late by 2.02 cents a gallon to 66.86 cents while heating oil dropped 2.51 cents a gallon to 69.62 cents.
Lower NYMEX prices helped pushed CARB gasoline one cent lower from the morning to 69.75/70.50 cents a gallon.
Fundamentals were weakened by a report that PADD 5 West Coast gasoline stocks rose 5.63 million barrels last week, and stood 1.9 million over year-ago levels.
But strength came from ongoing reports of lost production at the region's refineries.
In Richmond, Calif., Chevron's fluid catalytic cracker (FCC), a unit which puts about 50,000 barrels-per-day of gasoline into California markets, will remain down through December 25, sources said.
The news helped lift bids for conventional grade gasoline a half cent to 68.50 cents a gallon late Tuesday.
Bay-area gasolines rose to parity with L.A. grades, lifted by talk of tightness following the Richmond problem.
